 historical and social consciousness arising from the ideal of the classical republic revived by Machiavelli and other thinkers of Renaissance Italy. Pocock shows that Machiavelli's prime emphasis was on the moment in which the republic confronts the problem of its own instability in time, which Pocock calls the "Machiavellian moment."After examining this problem in the works of Machiavelli, Guicciardini, and Giannotti, Pocock turns to the revival of republican ideology in Puritan England and in Revolutionary and Federalist America. He argues that the American Revolution can be considered the last great act of civic humanism of the Renaissance and he relates the origins of modern historicism to the clash between civic, Christian, and commercial values in eighteenth-century thought.This Princeton Classics edition of The Machiavellian Moment features a new introduction by Richard Whatmore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aAmerican Constitution.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAmerican consciousness.  aAnglicization.  aAristotle.  aArte della Guerra.  aBritain.  aC. H. McIlwain.  aChristian thought.  aCivil War.  aConsiglio Grande.  aDialogo.  aDiscorsi.  aDonato Giannotti.  aEngland.  aEnglish Machiavellianism.  aEnglish political order.  aEuropean history.  aEuropean politics.  aFederalism.  aFlorence.  aFlorentine government.  aFlorentine politics.  aFlorentine republic.  aFlorentine republican tradition.  aFlorentine thought.  aFrancesco Guicciardini.  aGasparo Contarini.  aGiannotti.  aGiovanni Cavalcanti.  aGirolamo Savonarola.  aGod.  aGuicciardini.  aHarringtonian republicanism.  aIl Principe.  aInterregnum.  aJohn Fortescue.  aLeonardo Bruni.  aMachiavelli.  aMachiavellian moment.  aMachiav